<sect1 id="swarm.user.user1.03.sect1">
  <title>The notion of a Swarm</title>

<sect2>
 <title>The (Swarm) OOP way</title> 

    <para>Each agent saves his own behavior and state and acts when called upon by 
      scheduler or other agents.
    </para>
    <para>The event loop is now embedded in an object that sends messages to agents 
      and objects</para>
</sect2>

<sect2>
 <title>The Swarms</title> 

    <formalpara><title>A Swarm is an object that implements</title>
      <para>
        <itemizedlist>
          <listitem>memory allocation</listitem>            
          <listitem>management of scheduling mechanism</listitem>
        </itemizedlist>
      </para>
    </formalpara>

    <formalpara><title>A basic Swarm simulation consists of</title>
      <para>
        <itemizedlist>
          <listitem>Observer Swarm</listitem>
          <listitem>Model Swarm</listitem>
          <listitem>Agents</listitem>
          <listitem>Inanimate objects</listitem>
          <listitem>Widgets</listitem>
          <listitem>Probes</listitem>
          <listitem>Observer</listitem>
          <listitem>Model</listitem>
        </itemizedlist>
    </para></formalpara> 

</sect2>

<sect2>
 <title>The recursive structure of Swarms</title> 

    <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>Swarm </listitem>
      <listitem>Sub-Swarm    </listitem>
      <listitem>Agent        </listitem>
      <listitem>Schedule     </listitem>
      <listitem>The Interface</listitem>
      <listitem>The Model    </listitem>
      <listitem>Probes       </listitem>
      <listitem>Sub-sub-Swarm</listitem>
    </itemizedlist>

</sect2>

<sect2>
 <title>A Swarm as a virtual computer</title> 

    <para> Operating System
      Swarm kernel
      GUI
      Model
    </para>

<formalpara><title>A computer's CPU executes program instructions</title>
              <para></para></formalpara>

    <formalpara><title>Swarm kernel is sort of virtual CPU 
        running model and GUI events</title><para>
      </para></formalpara>

    <formalpara><title>Nested Swarms merge schedules into one</title><para>
        CPU</para></formalpara>

</sect2>

<sect2>
 <title>The Activity framework</title> 


    <formalpara><title>Provides abstractions that allow programmer to treat event scheduling in the artificial world as objects, separate from elements of model
</title><para></para>
    </formalpara>

    <formalpara><title>Provide some useful shorthands to group actions and sort according to the desired order of events
</title>
      <para></para>
    </formalpara>

    <formalpara><title>Since schedules are objects, all agents in simulation can communicate with them, to schedule future events or cause actions to be dropped based on specified contingencies</title><para>
</para></formalpara> 

</sect2>
</sect1>
